{
  "roast_critique": "John, your resume reads like a corporate motivational poster on steroids. You start with the classic \"Results‑driven marketing strategist\" line, followed by a parade of buzzwords—\"data‑centric\", \"cross‑functional collaboration\", \"predictive scoring model\"—as if sprinkling glitter will hide the fact that you’re basically saying \"I did stuff and it was great\". You brag about \"Lead a team of 5 analysts and designers\" like it’s a heroic feat, yet you never explain what those five actually accomplished beyond pretty numbers. \"Managed a $1.2M annual budget\" sounds impressive until we discover you didn’t clarify ROI or cost savings. And that \"Generated 5,400 trial sign‑ups in the first month\" for a tele‑health launch? Nice hustle, but without churn or conversion data it’s just a vanity metric. In short, you’re dropping numbers like confetti without any context, and the whole thing smells like a self‑congratulatory press release.",
  "professional_suggestions": [
    "Add context to every metric (e.g., conversion rates, revenue impact, or percentage of total pipeline) so recruiters can gauge the real business value of your achievements.",
    "Trim the buzzword overload and focus each bullet on a specific problem you solved, the action you took, and the measurable outcome—keep it concise and results‑focused.",
    "Tailor the professional summary to the target role, include soft‑skill highlights (leadership, stakeholder management), and ensure consistent formatting (e.g., use a clickable LinkedIn URL and uniform date styles)."
  ],
  "rating": 8
}

{
  "roast_critique": "Nina, your résumé reads like a marketing textbook that was written by a buzzword‑generator. The opening line – \"Strategic Marketing Communications professional with 7 years of experience driving brand growth, demand generation, and content strategy\" – is the exact copy‑paste you’ll see on every LinkedIn profile, and the rest of the document is a parade of percentages (42 % more leads, 18 % higher brand recall, 67 % traffic lift) that never explain *why* they matter to the bottom line. You even brag about managing a $3.2 M budget without ever mentioning the ROI dollars you actually delivered. And, of course, you cling to the fossil‑era \"References available upon request\" line like it’s a relic from the 1990s, while your portfolio URL drops the required https:// prefix, making recruiters wonder if you’re still living in the Web 1.0 era.",
  "professional_suggestions": [
    "Rewrite the Professional Summary into a punchy 2‑sentence value proposition that ties your 7 years of experience to concrete business results (e.g., revenue uplift, cost savings) and strip out generic buzzwords.",
    "Update the contact section: add the full https:// prefix to your LinkedIn and Portfolio URLs, and replace the outdated \"References available upon request\" line with a brief note directing recruiters to your portfolio or a LinkedIn recommendations page.",
    "For each quantified achievement, add a short business context (e.g., \"generated $1.2 M in pipeline revenue\" or \"saved $250 K in ad spend\") and insert at least one soft‑skill bullet (team leadership, stakeholder alignment, cross‑functional communication) to balance the heavy metrics focus."
  ],
  "rating": 8
}

{
  "roast_critique": "Sofia, your résumé reads like a promotional flyer for every cloud‑native buzzword under the sun. You open with the generic \"Detail‑oriented Software Engineer\"—as if nobody ever actually puts \"detail‑oriented\" on a cover letter—then immediately drown us in hyper‑specific stats: \"handling >10 M daily API requests with 99.97 % uptime\" and \"cutting deployment time from 45 minutes to under 5 minutes\" like you’re auditioning for a speed‑run competition. The “architected and implemented a container‑based micro‑service suite …” line sounds impressive until you realize you never explain *why* that mattered to the business. Your “Created CI pipelines … achieving 100 % test coverage for critical services” brag is nice, but it reads like a checklist rather than a story of solved problems. And, of course, you end with the antiquated “References: Available upon request,” as if that will magically make a hiring manager chase you. In short, you’ve packed the resume with metrics and jargon, but you’ve left out the human context that actually convinces someone to hire you.",
  "professional_suggestions": [
    "Rewrite the Professional Summary to focus on a clear value proposition and one or two standout outcomes, dropping vague adjectives like \"detail‑oriented\" and emphasizing what you uniquely deliver to a prospective employer.",
    "Add brief context to each metric (e.g., business impact, team size, revenue relevance) so the numbers become a narrative of problems solved rather than a laundry‑list of percentages and uptimes.",
    "Remove the stale \"References: Available upon request\" line, and instead include a concise soft‑skill/leadership bullet (e.g., stakeholder communication, cross‑functional collaboration) to balance the heavy technical focus."
  ],
  "rating": 8
}

